Loan Data Exploration¶

by Yiming Zhao¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a dataset containing 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 loans in the dataset with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, credit scores, and many others.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in figuring out what factors affect a loan's outcome status, and the borrower's APR or interest rate?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that several factors will have a negative effect on the loan interest rate, such as a loaner's credit score and debt to income ratio. Some factors such as loan amount and delinquencies will also have effects on the loan interest rate.

Univariate Exploration¶

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main variable of interest: Borrower APR.

#investigating further on an even smaller bin size noticing the spike between 0.33 to 0.38
binsize=0.0005
bins = np.arange(0.33, 0.38, binsize)
plt.hist(data=loan, x='BorrowerAPR', bins=bins)
plt.xlim([0.33, 0.38])
plt.xlabel('Borrower APR');

In the case of borrower's APR, the small bin size proves that there are very large spikes in frequency at the bars around 0.358. This rate takes almost 5% of the APR in the dataset. Besides the large spike around 0.35 to 0.36, the borrower' APR is roughly normally distributed.

Next, we will take a look at borrower's interest rate, credit score, prosper's rating, debt to income ratio, income range, loan orignal amount.

In [9]:
#Borrower's Interest Rate
#since borrower's interest rate is part of borrower's APR, we will plot these two variables together to get an idea of each variable's distribution
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=2, figsize=[6,8])

variables = ['BorrowerAPR', 'BorrowerRate']
for i in np.arange(len(variables)):
    var = variables[i]
    bins = np.arange(min(loan[var]), max(loan[var])+0.005, 0.005)
    ax[i].hist(data=loan, x=var, bins=bins)
    ax[i].set_xlabel('{}'.format(var))
plt.show()

The plot of borrower's interest rate show some immediate points of attention. Interestingly, the interest rate also has a spike around 0.32 to 0.34 and is roughly normally distributed excluding the spike. As we can see, the rate lags a little bit for the APR. Interest rate is part of APR. And on top of the interest rate, there are some other expenses associated with the loan. It makes sense that APR lags a little behind than the interest rate. To some extent, it also reflects that interest rate is one of the main factors that impact APR.

The credit rating between prosper's rating numeric vs alpha is pretty consistent, with most of the borrowers under C for prosper rating alpha, and 4 for prosper rating numeric. Most borrowers are within prosper scores 4-7. It makes sense as prosper rating is the system prosper has developed to calculate the credit worthiness of customers. It takes into account similar factors.

In [30]:
def log_trans(x, inverse=False):
    if not inverse:
        return np.log10(x)
    else:
        return np.power(10,x)
loan['log_monthly_income'] = loan['StatedMonthlyIncome'].apply(lambda x:log_trans(x))
In [31]:
loan['log_principal'] = loan['ProsperPrincipalBorrowed'].apply(lambda x:log_trans(x))

What affects the borrower's APR. First of all, borrower's APR has almost a linear relationship with borrower's interest rate, which is what we expected. Secondly, principal tend to have a negative impact on borrower's APR. In addition, on average, shorter term loan tend to have lower APR, but the APR doesn't vary that much. Lastly, borrowers with higher prosper score tend to have lower APR.

As far as borrower's income, it appears that the borrower's APR ranges vary widely. But on average, borrower's with higher income tend to have lower borrower's APR.
